{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_011JqQqCVy9BAjnE19wAMus3","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Exploration Notes\n     2→\n     3→## Key Files & Roles\n     4→\n     5→- `AGENTS.md` — repository guardrails for Bash 3.2 compatibility, output contract, and workflow expectations.\n     6→- `skills/npm-agent/scripts/npm-agent.sh` — current agent pattern with shared defaults, step timing, cleanup, and `--help` usage.\n     7→- `skills/cargo-agent/scripts/cargo-agent.sh` — shows lock+cleanup precedence, nextest integration, and verbose `overall_ok` flow.\n     8→- `skills/terra-agent/scripts/terra-agent.sh` — shows optional tool skip behavior and terraform-specific lock/cleanup conventions.\n     9→- `skills/*/SKILL.md` — shared metadata schema including `allowed-tools` and trigger language.\n    10→- `install.sh` — local vs remote install modes, optional dependency checks, and destination patching.\n    11→- `tests/run-scenarios.sh` — authoritative test harness contract for all agents; shellcheck plus scenario fixture execution.\n    12→- `tests/*/scenario.env` — scenario metadata (`SCENARIO_NAME`, `AGENT_SCRIPT`, `RUN_ARGS`, `EXPECT_EXIT`, `REQUIRED_TOOLS`).\n    13→- `tests/cargo-agent/flock/flock-test.sh` — current lock integration test for waiting on lock acquisition.\n    14→- `docs/agents/add-x-agent.md` — how new agents are expected to be structured, including boilerplate expectations and install updates.\n    15→- `docs/agents/scenario-tests.md` — fixture conventions and execution format.\n    16→- `docs/agents/definition-of-done.md` — acceptance contract for each agent.\n    17→- `docs/testing.md` — testing and CI matrix expectations.\n    18→- `.github/workflows/ci.yml` — shellcheck job and per-agent scenario execution matrix.\n    19→- `README.md` — user-facing discoverability for available agents and quick command references.\n    20→- `.ralph/specs/01-shared-library-extract.md` — explicit FR list for spec 01.\n    21→\n    22→## Patterns & Conventions\n    23→\n    24→- Bash headers are standardized: `#!/usr/bin/env bash` + `set -euo pipefail`.\n    25→- Output contract is strict and machine-aided: each step prints `Step:`, `Result: PASS|FAIL|SKIP`, optional `Fix:`, and `Time:`; final section prints `Overall:` and `Logs:`.\n    26→- `MAX_LINES` is CI-aware; local defaults are concise and CI allows large output (`MAX_LINES=999999`).\n    27→- Step failure handling is controlled by an `overall_ok` accumulator and `should_continue` guard.\n    28→- Cleanup trap pattern preserves logs on failure and optionally keeps them on success via `KEEP_DIR`.\n    29→- Optional tools are converted to skip or degraded behavior instead of hard failures.\n    30→- `--help|help|-h` and `--fail-fast` are user-facing entry points for agent control flow.\n    31→- Installer supports two modes: local checkout mode (symlink `skills/*`) and remote mode (copied skill directory).\n    32→\n    33→## Database Schema\n    34→\n    35→No database layer exists in this repository.\n    36→\n    37→## Test Infrastructure\n    38→\n    39→- `tests/run-scenarios.sh` drives all behavior checks and is the common validation entrypoint.\n    40→- Shellcheck runs first (or as dedicated CI job) using `--severity=warning` across `skills/*/scripts/*.sh`, `install.sh`, and test scripts.\n    41→- Scenarios are discovered by finding `tests/*/scenario.env`; each fixture runs via its `AGENT_SCRIPT` in fixture directory.\n    42→- Missing dependencies in scenario `REQUIRED_TOOLS` cause a soft `SKIP` instead of hard failure.\n    43→- `tests/cargo-agent/flock` extends coverage to lock behavior via a background lock holder helper script.\n    44→- CI runs separate jobs per agent and matrix variants for optional tools (e.g., no nextest/tflint vs with tools).\n    45→\n    46→## Architecture & Data Flow\n    47→\n    48→- Entry point: a single agent script executed from project root; it parses CLI flags, sets run-mode globals, and calls step functions in order.\n    49→- Shared boilerplate currently resides inside each script; extraction moves it into a central `lib/x-agent-common.sh` while preserving call points.\n    50→- Runtime flow is: initialize env defaults → resolve dependencies with `need()` → prepare output directory + lock → run selected command path (`format/check/test/...`) → print per-step output → print overall status.\n    51→- Logging flow: each step writes to `$OUTDIR/<step>.log`; failure paths print a bounded snippet and preserve `OUTDIR` path.\n    52→- Install flow: `install.sh` copies or symlinks skills, then rewrites `SKILL.md` paths depending on install mode; this currently does not propagate shared `lib/` for remote installs.\n    53→- Test flow: local invocation and CI both rely on the same scenario runner; changes must remain compatible with both.\n    54→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"226048e6-738a-41d7-adea-ced326c6394c","uuid":"54c6c04f-73ac-4ef5-833c-901f9de021a8","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/chrisraethke/projects/x-agent/.ralph/exploration.md","content":"# Exploration Notes\n\n## Key Files & Roles\n\n- `AGENTS.md` — repository guardrails for Bash 3.2 compatibility, output contract, and workflow expectations.\n- `skills/npm-agent/scripts/npm-agent.sh` — current agent pattern with shared defaults, step timing, cleanup, and `--help` usage.\n- `skills/cargo-agent/scripts/cargo-agent.sh` — shows lock+cleanup precedence, nextest integration, and verbose `overall_ok` flow.\n- `skills/terra-agent/scripts/terra-agent.sh` — shows optional tool skip behavior and terraform-specific lock/cleanup conventions.\n- `skills/*/SKILL.md` — shared metadata schema including `allowed-tools` and trigger language.\n- `install.sh` — local vs remote install modes, optional dependency checks, and destination patching.\n- `tests/run-scenarios.sh` — authoritative test harness contract for all agents; shellcheck plus scenario fixture execution.\n- `tests/*/scenario.env` — scenario metadata (`SCENARIO_NAME`, `AGENT_SCRIPT`, `RUN_ARGS`, `EXPECT_EXIT`, `REQUIRED_TOOLS`).\n- `tests/cargo-agent/flock/flock-test.sh` — current lock integration test for waiting on lock acquisition.\n- `docs/agents/add-x-agent.md` — how new agents are expected to be structured, including boilerplate expectations and install updates.\n- `docs/agents/scenario-tests.md` — fixture conventions and execution format.\n- `docs/agents/definition-of-done.md` — acceptance contract for each agent.\n- `docs/testing.md` — testing and CI matrix expectations.\n- `.github/workflows/ci.yml` — shellcheck job and per-agent scenario execution matrix.\n- `README.md` — user-facing discoverability for available agents and quick command references.\n- `.ralph/specs/01-shared-library-extract.md` — explicit FR list for spec 01.\n\n## Patterns & Conventions\n\n- Bash headers are standardized: `#!/usr/bin/env bash` + `set -euo pipefail`.\n- Output contract is strict and machine-aided: each step prints `Step:`, `Result: PASS|FAIL|SKIP`, optional `Fix:`, and `Time:`; final section prints `Overall:` and `Logs:`.\n- `MAX_LINES` is CI-aware; local defaults are concise and CI allows large output (`MAX_LINES=999999`).\n- Step failure handling is controlled by an `overall_ok` accumulator and `should_continue` guard.\n- Cleanup trap pattern preserves logs on failure and optionally keeps them on success via `KEEP_DIR`.\n- Optional tools are converted to skip or degraded behavior instead of hard failures.\n- `--help|help|-h` and `--fail-fast` are user-facing entry points for agent control flow.\n- Installer supports two modes: local checkout mode (symlink `skills/*`) and remote mode (copied skill directory).\n\n## Database Schema\n\nNo database layer exists in this repository.\n\n## Test Infrastructure\n\n- `tests/run-scenarios.sh` drives all behavior checks and is the common validation entrypoint.\n- Shellcheck runs first (or as dedicated CI job) using `--severity=warning` across `skills/*/scripts/*.sh`, `install.sh`, and test scripts.\n- Scenarios are discovered by finding `tests/*/scenario.env`; each fixture runs via its `AGENT_SCRIPT` in fixture directory.\n- Missing dependencies in scenario `REQUIRED_TOOLS` cause a soft `SKIP` instead of hard failure.\n- `tests/cargo-agent/flock` extends coverage to lock behavior via a background lock holder helper script.\n- CI runs separate jobs per agent and matrix variants for optional tools (e.g., no nextest/tflint vs with tools).\n\n## Architecture & Data Flow\n\n- Entry point: a single agent script executed from project root; it parses CLI flags, sets run-mode globals, and calls step functions in order.\n- Shared boilerplate currently resides inside each script; extraction moves it into a central `lib/x-agent-common.sh` while preserving call points.\n- Runtime flow is: initialize env defaults → resolve dependencies with `need()` → prepare output directory + lock → run selected command path (`format/check/test/...`) → print per-step output → print overall status.\n- Logging flow: each step writes to `$OUTDIR/<step>.log`; failure paths print a bounded snippet and preserve `OUTDIR` path.\n- Install flow: `install.sh` copies or symlinks skills, then rewrites `SKILL.md` paths depending on install mode; this currently does not propagate shared `lib/` for remote installs.\n- Test flow: local invocation and CI both rely on the same scenario runner; changes must remain compatible with both.\n","numLines":54,"startLine":1,"totalLines":54}}}
